1 Section 1. Chapter 277A of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
2 section to read as follows:
3 1. In a county whose population is 100,000 or more, a commission shall:
4 (a) Install and maintain appropriate infrastructure and technology designed
5 to mitigate safety risks to transit operators, including, without limitation, the use
6 of:
7 (1) Barriers to restrict the unwanted entry of passengers and
8 unauthorized persons and objects into the workstation of a transit operator; and
9 (2) Panic buttons and other technology designed to mitigate safety risks
10 to transit operators.
11 (b) Install and maintain appropriate signage informing the public about the
12 criminal penalties for crimes committed against transit operators or the public,
13 including, without limitation, the criminal penalties for:
14 (1) Assault of a transit operator pursuant to NRS 200.471; and
15 (2) Battery of a transit operator pursuant to NRS 200.481 . [; and
16 (3) Violation of a public transportation trespass order pursuant to section
17 2 of this act.]
18 2. As used in this section, “transit operator” [has the meaning ascribed to it
19 in NRS 200.471.] means a person who holds a commercial driver’s license issued
20 pursuant to NRS 483.900 to 483.940, inclusive, and who operates a bus or other
21 vehicle:
22 (a) As part of a public mass transportation system; and
23 (b) For which the person is required to hold a commercial driver’s license
24 issued pursuant to NRS 483.900 to 483.940, inclusive, to operate the bus or other
25 vehicle.
26 Sec. 2. [Chapter 200 of NRS is hereby amended by adding thereto a new
27 section to read as follows:
28 1. If a person is convicted of a violation of NRS 200.471 or 200.481
29 committed upon a transit operator, the governmental entity operating the public
30 mass transportation system for which the transit operator was performing his or
31 her duties may petition the district court in the county in which the violation
32 occurred for the issuance of a public transportation trespass order pursuant to
33 this section.
34 2. A petition for the issuance of a public transportation trespass order filed
35 pursuant to this section must include all of the following information:
36 (a) Evidence of the conviction of the person against whom the order is
37 sought for a violation of NRS 200.471 or 200.481.
38 (b) A detailed statement of facts demonstrating that the order is necessary to
39 protect public safety and transit operations.
40 (c) The proposed duration and scope of the order, which must not exceed 18
41 months.
42 3. Within 30 days after a petition for the issuance of a public transportation
43 trespass order is filed pursuant to this section, the court shall hold a hearing to
44 determine whether to issue the order. The person against whom the order is
45 sought is entitled to notice of the hearing and an opportunity to be heard at the
46 hearing.

