1 4. The court may issue a public transportation trespass order pursuant to
2 this section if the court finds, by a preponderance of the evidence, that:
3 (a) The person against whom the order is sought poses a continuing threat to
4 public safety or transit operations; and
5 (b) The order is necessary to protect public safety or to prevent future
6 disruptions to transit operations.
7 5. A public transportation trespass order issued pursuant to this section
8 may, with respect to the person against whom the order is issued, do any or all of
9 the following:
10 (a) Prohibit the person from entering onto the property of the public mass
11 transportation system for a specified period not to exceed 18 months;
12 (b) Limit the access of the person to transit services offered by the public
13 mass transportation for a specified period not to exceed 18 months; or
14 (c) Impose any other appropriate restrictions or prohibitions on the person
15 with respect to entering the property of the public mass transportation system or
16 using the transit services offered by the public mass transportation system.
17 6. A public transportation trespass order issued pursuant to this section
18 must be consistent with all other applicable federal, state or local laws that
19 protect civil rights and ensure public access to a public mass transportation
20 system.
21 7. A person who is subject to a public transportation trespass order issued
22 pursuant to this section and who violates such an order is guilty of a
23 misdemeanor.
24 8. A person against whom a public transportation trespass order has been
25 issued pursuant to this section may, at any time after issuance of the order, file a
26 petition with the court that issued the order requesting modification or
27 termination of the order. Within 30 days after a petition for modification or
28 termination of an order is filed pursuant to this section, the court shall hold a
29 hearing to determine whether to modify or terminate the order. The governmental
30 entity that filed the petition for the order is entitled to notice of the hearing and
31 an opportunity to be heard at the hearing. If the court finds, by a preponderance
32 of the evidence, that modification or termination of the order is warranted and
33 would not jeopardize public safety or transit operations, the court may modify or
34 terminate the order.
35 9. A governmental entity that operates a public mass transportation system
36 shall:
37 (a) Maintain records of any public transportation trespass order issued
38 pursuant to this section; and
39 (b) Periodically review those records to ensure proportionality and fairness.
